The code that we used in R programming to achieve 122500 x 2601 array is below, but it lasts very much time to run the code and take output. So we decided to do this part of the project in python¶


df<-array(0,dim = c(122500,2601))
df<-data.frame(df)
image_windows<-img_g

for (i in c(1:1)) {
lleft<-(i)
lright<-(50+i)

for(j in c(1:350)){
new_windows<-image_windows[j:(50+j),lleft:lright]
dim(new_windows)<-c(1,2601)
a<-j+(i-1)*350
df[a,]<-new_windows
} }

In here we extracted all possible patches of our image and the package extracted 122500 patch.Because the all possible patches are 51 x 51 array, so we should form 1 x 2601 array for all of these images to create a linear regression model.¶

model_array=pd.DataFrame(model_array)

Because the 1301. pixel of all patches gives the center pixel,1301. columns will be the output or dependent variable and the remaining columns will be predictors of the center pixel.¶

When we tried to make linear regression by using all 122500 rows, lm.fit function gave memory error . Therefore we selected randomly 60000 rows and constructed one regression model for those pixels and predicted our y values according to that model.However when we tried to run lm function with 122500 rows in another computer we were able take results, so we continued with that computer and also left our first code here.¶

newArray=random.sample(range(0, 122500), 60000)

random_array=0
random_array=pd.DataFrame

k=newArray[0]
random_array=model_array.loc[[k]]
for i in range(59999):
k=newArray[i+1]
random_array=random_array.append(model_array.loc[[k]])

lm=LinearRegression()
lm.fit(random_array.drop(columns=[1301]),random_array[1301])
predicted_pixels=lm.predict(X)

In [14]:
mean=statistics.mean(residuals)
std=statistics.stdev(residuals)
UCL=mean+3*std
LCL=mean-3*std

fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(18,10))
ax.plot(residuals)
ax.plot(np.linspace(UCL,UCL,122500),color="red")
ax.plot(np.linspace(LCL,LCL,122500),color="red")
ax.plot(np.linspace(mean,mean,122500),color="yellow")
ax.set_title(" Control chart for residuals")

We extracted all possible patches, which is totally 122500 patches, of our image and we combined those patches pixel values in 122500 x 2601 array.Because 1301. column of each row corresponds to center pixel we fitted our linear regression model according to this column and other columns.After constructing our model we predicted center pixels by using that model and compared that predicted values with the real values.We plotted histogram and qq plot of the residuals and we saw that the residuals are normally distributed.Finally we assumed K=3 and constructed 3 sigma control limits.After plotting the X bar chart of the residuals we changed the pixel values that are out of control limits.¶

One way of reducing autocorrelation is to remove one or more of the violating predictors from the regression model. Another way is to collect additional data under different experimental or observational conditions.¶
